Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The white wines dataset has 4,898 records and 12 columns/variables originally (excluding the X/ID variable). All the feature variables (thus also excluding quality) have continuous values.

As seen in the above histograms, for most variables, data is rather normally distributed (with or without long tails); alcohol and residual.sugar are the most evident exceptions.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The quality feature is the output variable, in this dataset ranging from a score of 3 to 9. I am no expert myself, but as someone who appreciates wine I am led to think that the main characteristics that make up a good quality wine are acidity and sugar, which will then be the first variables I will analyze.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Appearing as two related measures (free and total), I believe sulfur dioxide must have a more direct influence in the quality of wine, probably along with sulphates and the pH.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created the bound.sulfur.dioxide variable based on the total.sulfur.dioxide amount minus the portion indicated as free.sulfur.dioxide.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I noticed an unusual distribution of the residual.sugar variable. It peaks at values close to 0, so I decided to analyze it using a log10 transformation. With the new scale, it showed a bimodal distribution.

The alcohol variable also has a unique distribution compared to the other ones, as it appears to be more linear (decreasing).

In many cases, I changed the binwidth in the charts for a better view. Some distributions were found to have long tails as well.

Now let’s take a closer look at the boxplots for quality, since they display too small in the ggpairs matrix output.

For some boxplots we can see that there are fewer outliers and narrower interquartile ranges as quality increases, for example in the above boxplot of total.sulfur.dioxide.

Actually many of the above bloxplots show narrower interquartile ranges as quality increases. This will be discussed in more detail in the following section.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

A very interesting observation extracted from the above boxplots is that for several variables the interquartile range for wines of quality 9 is generally much narrower than those of lower quality wines. This is particularly true for variables residual.sugar, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, sulphates and alcohol.

Even considering there are just 5 wines of quality 9 in this dataset, such narrow value ranges could suggest these variables are some kind of “baseline” value for a wine to be considered of higher quality. Considering that these input variables are measured by physicochemical tests while the output variable quality is scored based on sensory evaluation, it is really interesting to note that experts seem to be able to rate the quality of a wine based on very specific characteristics only by using their senses.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

By looking at the boxplots and the correlation matrix, an inverse/negative relationship can be observed between the quality of wine and its density…

… which in turn has a stronger and more linear correlation with alcohol and residual.sugar, as can be seen in the two charts below.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Several variables seem to have a strong relationship with the quality of wine, as discussed above for the boxplots and the narrow interquartile ranges. The two that show the strongest relationships so far are alcohol and density; however, from the boxplots we can also note that chlorides and total.sulfur.dioxide seem to have a rather linear relationship with quality as well.

Having analyzed these variables, let’s now create a model. We will iteratively add variables to the model to see which variables contribute more to a higher R2 value.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

In the histograms colored by quality, trends can be seen with higher quality wines having volatile.acidity values lower than 0.3, chlorides values between 0.025 and 0.05, total.sulfur.dioxide values between 90 and 160, density values between 0.99 and 0.995, and alcohol values greater than 10.5, as initially indicated by the quality boxplots.

In the scatterplots, the relationship between some variables (other than quality) becomes clearer. In the first scatterplot, it is visible that higher quality wines are more commonly found at lower values of residual.sugar (less than 10) and also lower density (less than 0.994). The second scatterplot follows the same logic as the previous one, with the darker blue dots (higher quality wines) being more commonly found for density values of 0.994 and lower, and for alcohol values of 11 and above. The last scatterplot is a combination of the previous ones, where most higher quality wines can be found for lower values of residual.sugar and higher values of alcohol.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

The relationship between more volume of alcohol and less density is personally a surprising finding, despite being already described in the White Wine Quality information document.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

A linear model was created using several variables, which were added iteratively to check the effect that each had on the results. The selected variables account for only 28.2% of the variance in the quality of wines. The ones that contribute most to this value of R2 are alcohol and volatile.acidity, which alone account for an R2 = 0.24.

This model using 8 variables and having an R2 value of only 0.282 is very limited, but this appears to be due to the nature of the dataset. The quality score is based on the sensory evaluation of 3 wine experts and, as explained in the White Wine Quality information document, support vector machine is the model that achieves the best results according to the dataset authors. As we proceed to Project 4 and learn about machine learning, it could be interesting to test a support vector machine model with this white wines dataset and see how it improves the results.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot 1 - Histogram of wines by quality

Description

The distribution of wines by quality is rather normal, with the vast majority being of quality 5 to 7.

Plot 2 - Histogram of wines by alcohol and quality

Description

This histogram provides a clear view of how alcohol is related to the quality of wines. Wines of quality 6 and above are found in clearly higher proportions for alcohol volumes of 9.5% and above.

Plot 3 - Scatterplot of wine quality by residual sugar and density

Description

This scatterplot shows that, for the same levels of residual sugar (x-axis constant), higher quality wines tend to have lower density. This can be seen as “stripes” in the scatterplot (variation in the y-axis holding the values in the x-axis constant), with the top of the curve being mostly composed by lighter blue dots (wine quality 6 or less) and the bottom of the curve being mostly darker blue (wine quality 7 or more). Another obvious conclusion from this scatterplot is that density increases as the residual sugar also increases.

Reflection

With the first plotted histogram (count of wines by quality), it already became clear that this white wines dataset was not balanced and contained many more regular wines (of quality 5 to 7) than poor or excellent ones. Wines of quality 5 to 7 make up over 92.5% of the total and this unbalanced distribution could have an impact on the analysis conducted. Also, the dataset has 11 input variables, which right from the beginning made me wonder whether all of them would be relevant or not for the analysis. I noticed some variables are correlated or dependent on each other, for example, free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide, and density, residual.sugar and alcohol. This is also mentioned in the White Wine Quality information document and is one of the reasons why I tested most if not all of the variables when creating the linear model.

Before creating the model, some of the multivariate plots already gave a good indication of which variables have the strongest relation with quality, most notably sulphates, volatile.acidity and alcohol. However, when creating a linear model to predict quality the best combination of variables tested could only lead to an R2 = 0.282. Linear models are known to be a very simple approach and thus provide only a limited solution to this specific problem. As explained in the White Wine Quality information document as well, the authors have tested this dataset and found that the model that achieves the best results is support vector machine. As we proceed to Project 4 and learn about machine learning, it could be interesting to test a support vector machine model with this white wines dataset and see how it improves the results.
